                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 1832</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member Ransom<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 11, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;">An act to add Section 8588.4 to the Government Code, relating to communications.</span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 1832, as amended, Ransom.
                          2-1-1 information and referral response system.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law, the California Emergency Services Act, creates, within the office of the Governor, the Office of Emergency Services (Cal OES) under the supervision of the Director of Emergency Services. Under existing law, Cal OES is responsible for the state’s emergency and disaster response services for natural, technological, or man-made disasters and emergencies, including responsibility for activities necessary to prevent, respond to, recover from, and mitigate the effects of emergencies and disasters to people and property, as provided.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law vests the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) with regulatory authority over public utilities, including telephone corporations. Existing law requires local public agencies to establish a “9-1-1” emergency telephone number, as specified. Existing law also authorizes a local public agency to
			 establish a nonemergency “3-1-1” telephone system. Under existing federal law, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has designated “2-1-1” to be the national abbreviated dialing code to provide access to nonemergency community information and referral services. Pursuant to authority delegated by the FCC to state regulatory bodies and its existing statutory authority, the PUC has established procedures for implementing 2-1-1 dialing in California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would<font color="#B30000"><strike> require Cal OES to convene state emergency planning agencies and the 2-1-1 lead entity appointed by the PUC to establish communication channels between state emergency planning agencies, the 2-1-1 lead
			 entity, and 2-1-1 providers and to integrate 2-1-1 into the state emergency planning and emergency communications processes, as provided. The bill would require Cal OES
			 to support 2-1-1 providers in,</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> create in the State Treasury the 2-1-1 Fund and, upon appropriation by the Legislature, would require Cal OES to allocate moneys appropriated from the fund to the California 211 Providers Network to be used for,</i></font> among other things, enhancing critical 2-1-1 system capacity and service quality through core operating support, providing equitable access to 2-1-1 dialing and services, publishing a statewide 2-1-1 community needs data dashboard for use by state agencies, developing aligned systems and protocols with 9-1-1 and 9-8-8,<font color="#B30000"><strike> and implementing the duties of the 2-1-1 lead entity, as provided. The bill would require the 2-1-1 lead entity to conduct statewide 2-1-1 system activities, provide funding, if available, to local 2-1-1 providers,</strike></font> and<font color="#B30000"><strike> provide</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
			 providing</i></font> annual reports to Cal OES, as specified.<font color="#B30000"><strike> The bill would require
			 Cal OES to annually communicate 2-1-1 system funding needs to the Department of Finance and the office of the Governor for consideration in state budget planning. The bill would create in the State Treasury the 2-1-1 Fund to be
			 used, upon appropriation by the Legislature, for these purposes.</strike></font></div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">YES</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.5225176077365848"><div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> This act shall be known, and may be cited, as the 2-1-1 Infrastructure and Emergency Response Act.</div></div></div><div id="s20.6580430348959813"><div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SEC. 2.</h3> The Legislature finds and declares both of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(a) Californians must be able to access 2-1-1 essential community services and critical communications infrastructure year-round and during disasters.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Because the 2-1-1 system serves such a wide range of populations and service categories and has no dedicated funding source, unlike 9-1-1 and 9-8-8, it would benefit the public to create a fund to pool funding from different sources unless or until a dedicated funding source for the 2-1-1 system is identified.</div></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_3E930EEC-8BC4-4AA9-BD29-43BBE21F682B"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SEC. 3.</caml:Num><caml:ActionLine action="IS_ADDED" xlink:href="urn:caml:codes:GOV:caml#xpointer(%2Fcaml%3ALawDoc%2Fcaml%3ACode%2F%2Fcaml%3ALawSection%5Bcaml%3ANum%3D'8588.4'%5D)" xlink:label="fractionType: LAW_SECTION" xlink:type="locator">Section 8588.4 is added to the <caml:DocName>Government Code</caml:DocName>, to read:</caml:ActionLine><caml:Fragment><caml:LawSection id="id_6461C28E-7A2A-4DED-9A43-9FDED56E641B"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>8588.4.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_8126D644-5339-41F7-8A98-4689E64DAB9C"><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>The office shall convene state emergency planning agencies, including the Public Utilities Commission, the Department of Forestry and Fire Protection, the State Department of Social Services, the State Department of Public Health, and the 2-1-1 lead entity appointed by the Public Utilities Commission, to do both of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(1)<span class="EnSpace"/>Establish communication channels between state emergency planning agencies, the 2-1-1 lead entity appointed by the Public Utilities Commission, and 2-1-1 providers, as set forth in Public Utilities Commission Decision 11-09-016 (September 8, 2011), Decision Granting Authority to Provide Emergency Access to 211 Services in Counties and Localities Without Existing 211 Centers and to Appoint a 211 Lead Entity,
						including adding 2-1-1 to emergency notification and coordination channels.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>Integrate 2-1-1 into the state emergency planning and emergency communication processes.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></caml:Fragment></caml:BillSection></strike></font><div id="s40.1773433542527747"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>SEC. 3.</i></font></h3> <font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Section 8588.4 is added to the Government Code, to read:</i></font></div><div><div id="id_6C6FDC1D-F3A9-4AB0-B049-52F2E4E2865E"><div><p><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>8588.4.</i></font></h6> (a) There is hereby created in the State Treasury the 2-1-1 Fund, the moneys in which shall be used for purposes of subdivisions (c) and (d), upon appropriation by the Legislature.</div></i></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The office shall allocate moneys appropriated from the 2-1-1 Fund to the California 211 Providers Network, also known as 211 California, to carry out the actions pursuant to subdivisions (c) and (d).</div></i></font><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>(b)</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>(c)</i></font> The<font color="#B30000"><strike> office shall support 2-1-1 providers in doing</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>
						moneys in the fund shall be used for</i></font> all of the<font color="#B30000"><strike> following:</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> following purposes:</i></font></div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Enhancing critical 2-1-1 system capacity and service quality through core operating support, including all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Staffing to handle 2-1-1 contacts.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Training, supervision, and quality assurance.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Consistent data collection and reporting.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Multilingual and multichannel access through modern
						technology and infrastructure.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Providing equitable access to 2-1-1 dialing and services by closing 2-1-1 coverage gaps and ensuring basic 2-1-1 service access statewide.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Publishing a statewide 2-1-1 community needs data dashboard for use by state agencies in monitoring and identifying community and disaster needs and resource gaps, and to inform efficient and responsive resource allocation.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Strengthening 2-1-1 community resource databases and enable resource data sharing and delivery to state agencies, health systems, and other key partners, and reduce redundancies in resource directory building and updating.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Developing
						aligned systems and protocols with 9-1-1 and 9-8-8 to strengthen integration and direct people to the right number for the right resources at the right time.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Promoting 2-1-1 awareness through public education and outreach opportunities.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(7) Improving 2-1-1 system readiness, infrastructure, and capacity to respond to disasters and all hazard events, including by doing all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Completing local and statewide 2-1-1 emergency operations plans.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Securing needed infrastructure updates, tools, protocols, and training for both local disaster response and statewide mutual aid and network response.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Engaging with local counties, cities, community-based organizations, and voluntary organizations active in disaster response planning, regarding the role of the 2-1-1 system and communication protocols.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Providing emergency funding for 2-1-1 disaster activation when local or philanthropic funding is not available or not sufficient to match 2-1-1 disaster contact volume.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(8)<span class="EnSpace"/>Implementing the duties of the 2-1-1 lead entity appointed by the Public Utilities Commission.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>The 2-1-1 lead entity appointed by the Public Utilities Commission shall do all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(1)<span class="EnSpace"/>Conduct statewide 2-1-1 system activities specified under this section.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>Provide funding, if available, to local 2-1-1 providers for activities specified under this section.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(3)<span class="EnSpace"/>Provide annual reports to the office on the 2-1-1 system
						status, use of any funds, and future 2-1-1 system funding needs.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>The office shall annually communicate 2-1-1 system funding needs to the Department of Finance and the office of the Governor for consideration in state budget planning.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(e)<span class="EnSpace"/>There is hereby created in the State Treasury the 2-1-1 Fund, the moneys in which shall be used for purposes of this section, upon appropriation by the Legislature.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) The California 211 Providers Network shall annually provide a report to the office on the 2-1-1 system
						status, use of any funds, and future 2-1-1 system funding needs.</div></i></font></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
